From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Armbian <build@armbian.com>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] scsi: ufs: issue native-4K I/O one block at a time

On Rock 4D, multi-block UFS READ returns OK but only the first 4096-byte
block is visible to the CPU (trailing blocks read as zeros). Confirmed
at the prompt:

  scsi read 0x42000000 0 2  -> LBA1 window empty
  scsi read 0x42000000 1 1  -> valid "EFI PART" GPT header

part_get_info_efi() then fails: GPT header is single-block (works) but
the 128-entry PTE array needs multiple 4K blocks (broken).

Until the UFSHCI PRDT/cache path is fixed properly, limit UFS
rawblksz==4096 max read/write chunk to 1 block.

--- a/drivers/scsi/scsi.c	2026-07-21 17:53:58.229107479 +0200
+++ b/drivers/scsi/scsi.c	2026-07-21 17:53:58.329108617 +0200
@@ -178,8 +178,14 @@
 	unsigned short smallblks = 0;
 	struct scsi_cmd *pccb = (struct scsi_cmd *)&tempccb;
 
+	/*
+	 * UFS native-4K multi-block DMA is unreliable on this stack: only the
+	 * first PRDT payload block is coherent. GPT PTE reads need >1 block.
+	 */
 	if (block_dev->rawblksz == 512)
 		max_read_blks = SCSI_MAX_READ_BLK;
+	else if (block_dev->rawblksz == 4096)
+		max_read_blks = 1;
 	else
 		max_read_blks = SCSI_UFS_MAX_READ_BLK;
 	/* Setup device */
@@ -315,6 +321,8 @@
 
 	if (block_dev->rawblksz == 512)
 		max_write_blks = SCSI_MAX_WRITE_BLK;
+	else if (block_dev->rawblksz == 4096)
+		max_write_blks = 1;
 	else
 		max_write_blks = SCSI_UFS_MAX_WRITE_BLK;
 
